# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arinc-653
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] It is part of ARINC 600-Series Standards for Digital Aircraft & Flight Simulators.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] In order to decouple the real-time operating system platform from the application software, ARINC 653 defines an API called APplication EXecutive (APEX).
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Each application software is called a **partition** and has its own memory space.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] It also has a dedicated time slot allocated by the APEX API.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Within each partition, multitasking is allowed.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The APEX API provides services to manage partitions, processes and timing, as well as partition/process communication and error handling.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The partitioning environment can be implemented by using a hypervisor to map partitions to virtual machines, but this is not required.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The standard is overseen by the AEEC APEX Subcommittee, which is co-chaired by representatives from Airbus and Boeing.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Gordon Putsche was the Boeing chair from 2002 until 2023.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] VanderLeest is the current Boeing chair.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Pierre Gabrilot is the current Airbus chair.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The initial version of ARINC 653 was published on October 10, 1996.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Supplement 1 was published in January 1997 and introduced the concepts of APEX and Time and Space partitioning.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Initialization of an ARINC 653 partition creates resources used by the partition.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Resources creation (PROCESS, EVENT, SEMAPHORE...) is performed by calling API services named **CREATE_xxxx**.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The process error handler is a preemptive process of the highest priority dedicated to handle partition exceptions.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] It is created by the service **CREATE_ERROR_HANDLER** during partition initialization.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The API allows the error handler to stop a faulty process (**STOP_SELF**).
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] In that case, the RTOS scheduler will elicit the next process with the highest priority.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] ARINC 653 does not specify how the scheduler should behave if the error handler does not stop a faulty process.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] In some (theoretical) cases, this could lead to an infinite loop between the faulty process and the error handler.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The error handler can obtain information about the source and the context of the exception.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The **SET_PARTITION_MODE** service allows to manage these states.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] It can be called by any process in the partition.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Entering the IDLE state is irreversible for the partition.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Only an external event (such as a platform restart) can change the state to another mode when the partition is in this state.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The standard defines a two-level hierarchical schedule.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The first level schedules the partitions.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] This is a round-robin, fixed schedule that repeats a Major Time Frame.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The Major Time Frame schedules each partition in a fixed duration Partition Time Window (sometimes called a Minor Time Frame) with a fixed Partition Time Window Offset from the start of the Major Time Frame.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] During the Partition Time Window, the second level of scheduling uses process scheduling.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Each partition has at least one process.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Process scheduling within a partition during the Partition Time Window is preemptive.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The scheduler is called either by a timer or by API services.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] ARINC 653 P1-5 was updated to address multicore processor architectures.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The position paper CAST-32A defines a set of requirements and guidance that should be met to certify and use multi-core processors in civil aviation by FAA and is expected to be replaced by an Advisory Circular, AC 20-193.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The European Union aviation authority, EASA, published AMC 20-193 in January 2022.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] No ARINC 653 services are provided for the memory management of partitions.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Each partition has to handle its own memory (still under the constraints of memory partitioning enforced by ARINC 653).
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] The field covered by ARINC 653 is similar to ASAAC *Def Stan 00-74*.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] However, there are differences between the two standards.
[src:arinc-653/arinc-653] Some ARINC 653 (APEX) calls have a POSIX equivalent, but are different from how they are defined in POSIX.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] ARINC was formerly headquartered in Annapolis, Maryland, and had two regional headquarters in London, established in 1999 to serve the Europe, Middle East, and Africa region, and Singapore, established in 2003 for the Asia Pacific region.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] ARINC had more than 3,200 employees at over 120 locations worldwide.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The sale of the company by Carlyle Group to Rockwell Collins was completed on December 23, 2013, and from November 2018 onward operates as part of Collins Aerospace.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] ARINC was incorporated in 1929 as Aeronautical Radio, Incorporated.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] It was chartered by the Federal Radio Commission (which later became the Federal Communications Commission) in order to serve as the airline industry's single licensee and coordinator of radio communication outside of the government.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The corporation's stock was held by four major airlines of the day.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] Through most of its history, ARINC was owned by airlines and other aviation-related companies such as Boeing until the sale to The Carlyle Group in October 2007.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] Not much later ARINC took on the responsibility for all ground-based, aeronautical radio stations and for ensuring station compliance with Federal Radio Commission (FRC) rules and regulations.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] Using this as a base technology, ARINC expanded its contributions to transport communications as well as continuing to support the commercial aviation industry and U.S. military.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] ARINC also developed the standards for the trays and boxes used to hold standard line-replaceable units (like radios) in aircraft.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] This subsequently allowed electronics to be rapidly replaced without complex fasteners or test equipment.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] ARINC has expanded its business in aerospace and defense through its ARINC Engineering Services subsidiary.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] With the sale of the company to Rockwell Collins, the ARINC Engineering Services subsidiary split into Commercial Aerospace and Defense Services.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The Defense Services branch was then purchased by Booz Allen Hamilton, remaining part of the Carlyle group.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The sale of a Standards Development Organization (SDP) to a corporate sponsor raised concerns of conflict of interest and resulted in the sale of the ARINC Industry Activities (IA) Division to SAE International in January 2014.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] It now operates under the SAE Industry Technologies Consortia (SAE ITC).
[src:arinc-653/arinc] United Technologies completed its acquisition of Rockwell Collins in November 2018 and merged it with its UTC Aerospace Systems to form Collins Aerospace.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] Though known for publishing "ARINC Standards", this role is independent of ARINC commercial activities.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The ARINC Standards are prepared by the Airlines Electronic Engineering Committee (AEEC) where aviation suppliers such as Collins Aerospace, GE Aerospace, and Universal Avionics serve as contributors in support of their airline customer base.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The 400 Series describes guidelines for installation, wiring, data buses, and databases.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The 500 Series describes older analog avionics equipment used on early jet aircraft such as the Boeing 727, Douglas DC-9, DC-10, Boeing 737 and 747, and Airbus A300.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The 700 Series describes the form, fit, and function of avionics equipment installed predominately on transport category aircraft.
[src:arinc-653/arinc] The 800 Series comprises a set of aviation standards for aircraft, including fiber optics used in high-speed data buses.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The basic idea of any software development model is that each step of the design process has outputs called "deliverables." If the deliverables are tested for correctness and fixed, then normal human mistakes can not easily grow into dangerous or expensive problems.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Most manufacturers follow the waterfall model to coordinate the design product, but almost all explicitly permit earlier work to be revised.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The result is more often closer to a spiral model.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] For an overview of embedded software see embedded system and software development models.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The rest of this article assumes familiarity with that information, and discusses differences between commercial embedded systems and commercial development models.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Since most avionics manufacturers see software as a way to add value without adding weight, the importance of embedded software in avionic systems is increasing.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Most modern commercial aircraft with auto-pilots use flight computers and so called flight management systems (FMS) that can fly the aircraft without the pilot's active intervention during certain phases of flight.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Also under development or in production are unmanned vehicles: missiles and drones which can take off, cruise and land without airborne pilot intervention.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] In many of these systems, failure is unacceptable.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The reliability of the software running in airborne vehicles (civil or military) is shown by the fact that most airborne accidents occur due to manual errors.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Unfortunately reliable software is not necessarily easy to use or intuitive, poor user interface design has been a contributing cause of many aerospace accidents and deaths.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Due to safety requirements, most nations regulate avionics, or at least adopt standards in use by a group of allies or a customs union.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The three regulatory organizations that most affect international aviation development are the U.S., the E.U. and Russia.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] In the U.S., avionic and other aircraft components have safety and reliability standards mandated by the Federal Aviation Regulations, Part 25 for Transport Airplanes, Part 23 for Small Airplanes, and Parts 27 and 29 for Rotorcraft.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] These standards are enforced by "designated engineering representatives" of the FAA who are usually paid by a manufacturer and certified by the FAA.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] In the European Union the IEC describes "recommended" requirements for safety-critical systems, which are usually adopted without change by governments.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A safe, reliable piece of avionics has a "CE Mark." The regulatory arrangement is remarkably similar to fire safety in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The government certifies testing laboratories, and the laboratories certify both manufactured items and organizations.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Essentially, the oversight of the engineering is outsourced from the government and manufacturer to the testing laboratory.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] To assure safety and reliability, national regulatory authorities (e.g. the FAA, CAA, or DOD) require software development standards.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Some representative standards include MIL-STD-2167 for military systems, or RTCA DO-178B and its successor DO-178C for civil aircraft.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The regulatory requirements for this software can be expensive compared to other software, but they are usually the minimum that is required to produce the necessary safety.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The main difference between avionics software and other embedded systems is that the actual standards are often far more detailed and rigorous than commercial standards, usually described by documents with hundreds of pages.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] It is usually run on a real time operating system.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Since the process is legally required, most processes have documents or software to trace requirements from numbered paragraphs in the specifications and designs to exact pieces of code, with exact tests for each, and a box on the final certification checklist.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] This is specifically to prove conformance to the legally mandated standard.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Deviations from a specific project to the processes described here can occur due to usage of alternative methods or low safety level requirements.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Almost all software development standards describe how to perform and improve specifications, designs, coding, and testing (See software development model).
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Projects with substantial human interfaces are usually prototyped or simulated.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The videotape is usually retained, but the prototype retired immediately after testing, because otherwise senior management and customers can believe the system is complete.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A major goal is to find human-interface issues that can affect safety and usability.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Safety-critical avionics usually have a hazard analysis.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The early stages of the project, already have at least a vague idea of the main parts of the project.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] An engineer then takes each block of a block diagram and considers the things that could go wrong with that block, and how they affect the system as a whole.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Subsequently, the severity and probability of the hazards are estimated.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The problems then become requirements that feed into the design's specifications.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Projects involving military cryptographic security usually include a security analysis, using methods very like the hazard analysis.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] As soon as the engineering specification is complete, writing the maintenance manual can start.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A maintenance manual is essential to repairs, and of course, if the system can't be fixed, it will not be safe.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] There are several levels to most standards.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A low-safety product such as an in-flight entertainment unit (a flying TV) may escape with a schematic and procedures for installation and adjustment.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A navigation system, autopilot or engine may have thousands of pages of procedures, inspections and rigging instructions.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Documents are now (2003) routinely delivered on CD-ROM, in standard formats that include text and pictures.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] One of the odder documentation requirements is that most commercial contracts require an assurance that system documentation will be available indefinitely.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The normal commercial method of providing this assurance is to form and fund a small foundation or trust.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The trust then maintains a mailbox and deposits copies (usually in ultrafiche) in a secure location, such as rented space in a university's library (managed as a special collection), or (more rarely now) buried in a cave or a desert location.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] These are usually much like those in other software development models.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A crucial difference is that requirements are usually traced as described above.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] In large projects, requirements-traceability is such a large expensive task that it requires large, expensive computer programs to manage it.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The code is written, then usually reviewed by a programmer (or group of programmers, usually independently) that did not write it originally (another legal requirement).
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Special organizations also usually conduct code reviews with a checklist of possible mistakes.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] When a new type of mistake is found it is added to the checklist, and fixed throughout the code.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The code is also often examined by special programs that analyze correctness (Static code analysis), such as SPARK examiner for the SPARK (a subset of the Ada programming language) or lint for the C-family of programming languages (primarily C, though).
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The compilers or special checking programs like "lint" check to see if types of data are compatible with the operations on them, also such tools are regularly used to enforce strict usage of valid programming language subsets and programming styles.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Another set of programs measure software metrics, to look for parts of the code that are likely to have mistakes.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] All the problems are fixed, or at least understood and double-checked.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Some code, such as digital filters, graphical user interfaces and inertial navigation systems, are so well understood that software tools have been developed to write the software.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] In these cases, specifications are developed and reliable software is produced automatically.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Unit test code is written to exercise every instruction of the code at least once to get 100% code coverage.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] A coverage tool is often used to verify that every instruction is executed, and then the test coverage is documented as well, for legal reasons.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] It forces detailed review of the program logic, and detects most coding, compiler and some design errors.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Some organizations write the unit tests *before* writing the code, using the software design as a module specification.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The unit test code is executed, and all the problems are fixed.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] As pieces of code become available, they are added to a skeleton of code, and tested in place to make sure each interface works.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Usually the built-in-tests of the electronics should be finished first, to begin burn-in and radio emissions tests of the electronics.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Next, the most important features of the software are integrated.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] At this stage, it is often beneficial for the integrators to have a way to run small, selected pieces of code, perhaps from a simple menu system.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Some program managers try to arrange this integration process so that after some minimal level of function is achieved, the system becomes deliverable at any following date, with increasing numbers of features as time passes.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Meanwhile, the test engineers usually begin assembling a test rig, and releasing preliminary tests for use by the software engineers.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] At some point, the tests cover all of the functions of the engineering specification.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] At this point, testing of the entire avionic unit begins.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The object of the acceptance testing is to prove that the unit is safe and reliable in operation.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The first test of the software, and one of the most difficult to meet in a tight schedule, is a realistic test of the unit's radio emissions.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] This usually must be started early in the project to assure that there is time to make any necessary changes to the design of the electronics.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The software is also subjected to a structural coverage analysis, where tests are run and code coverage is collected and analyzed.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] Each step produces a deliverable, either a document, code, or a test report.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] When the software passes all of its tests (or enough to be sold safely), these are bound into a certification report, that can literally have thousands of pages.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] The designated engineering representative, who has been striving for completion, then decides if the result is acceptable.
[src:arinc-653/avionics-software] If it is, he signs it, and the avionic software is certified.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] In opposition to traditional federated architectures, the IMA concept proposes an integrated architecture with application software portable across an assembly of common hardware modules.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] An IMA architecture imposes multiple requirements on the underlying operating system.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] It is believed that the IMA concept originated with the avionics design of the fourth-generation jet fighters.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] It has been in use in fighters such as F-22 and F-35, or Dassault Rafale since the beginning of the '90s.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] Standardization efforts were ongoing at this time (see ASAAC or STANAG 4626), but no final documents were issued then.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] Communication between the modules can use an internal high speed Computer bus, or can share an external network, such as ARINC 429 or ARINC 664 (part 7).
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] However, much complexity is added to the systems, which thus require novel design and verification approaches since applications with different criticality levels share hardware and software resources such as CPU and network schedules, memory, inputs and outputs.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] Partitioning is generally used in order to help segregate mixed criticality applications and thus ease the verification process.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] ARINC 650 and ARINC 651 provide general purpose hardware and software standards used in an IMA architecture.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] RTCA DO-178C and RTCA DO-254 form the basis for flight certification today, while DO-297 gives specific guidance for Integrated modular avionics.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] ARINC 653 contributes by providing a framework that enables each software building block (called a partition) of the overall Integrated modular avionics to be tested, validated, and qualified independently (up to a certain measure) by its supplier.
[src:arinc-653/integrated-modular-avionics] The FAA CAST-32A position paper provides information (not official guidance) for certification of multicore systems, but does not specifically address IMA with multicore.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:arinc-653/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] A **separation kernel** is a type of security kernel used to simulate a distributed environment.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] The concept was introduced by John Rushby in a 1981 paper.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] A variant of the separation kernel, the partitioning kernel, has gained acceptance in the commercial aviation community as a way of consolidating multiple functions onto a single processor, perhaps of mixed criticality.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] Commercial real-time operating system products in this genre have been used by aircraft manufacturers for safety-critical avionics applications.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] In 2007 the Information Assurance Directorate of the U.S.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] National Security Agency (NSA) published the Separation Kernel Protection Profile (SKPP), a security requirements specification for separation kernels suitable to be used in the most hostile threat environments.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] The SKPP describes, in Common Criteria parlance, a class of modern products that provide the foundational properties of Rushby's conceptual separation kernel.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] It defines the security functional and assurance requirements for the construction and evaluation of separation kernels while yet providing some latitude in the choices available to developers.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] In 2011, the Information Assurance Directorate sunset the SKPP.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] The seL4 microkernel has a formal proof of concept that it can be configured as a separation kernel.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] The enforced continuance of information along with this implies it is an elevated level example of assurance.
[src:arinc-653/separation-kernel] The Muen separation kernel is also a formally verified open source separation kernel for x86 machines.
